```class Solution {
public:
    int maxSubstrings(string word) {
        int res = 0, i = 0, n = word.size();
        unordered_map<char, int> mp;
        while (i < n) {
            char c = word[i];
            mp[c]++;
            while (mp[c] > 1) {
                mp[word[i]]--;
                i++;
            }
            if (i < n && word[i] == c) {
                res++;
                i++;
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
};```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: This solution uses a sliding window approach to keep track of the current substring. It uses a hashmap to store the frequency of each character in the current substring. When the frequency of a character exceeds 1, it means the current substring has at least one repeated character, so it moves the window forward until the frequency of the character becomes 1 again. If the current character is the same as the starting character of the substring, it means the substring is non-intersecting and starts and ends with the same letter, so it increments the result.

